WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:02.274
is this long-term memory right here.

00:02.694 --> 00:12.927
So in this memory, ideally, we would want to fit, let's say, an entire day, an entire week, or even an entire month of data from one of these cameras.

00:13.507 --> 00:22.478
And it's just not feasible that we expand this current window here to an entire month or an entire week.

00:22.458 --> 00:35.338
for many of those of those cameras because even though they have a low frame rate and so on it's still too much in order to then be all differentiable all back propagatable and so on.

00:36.200 --> 00:47.217
So we can't really back prop in for this long term memory in essence what we want to do is exactly the same we want to build up a memory

00:47.197 --> 01:06.302
of all of the regions of interest or maybe selected regions or all of the best regions of interest, whatever heuristic strategy we have of the past, whatever this camera has seen, let's say in the last month or in the current week or something like this, we want to build all of this up.

01:06.282 --> 01:11.347
and then use an attention mechanism, just the same in order to incorporate it.

01:11.688 --> 01:20.197
But we have to come up with these things right here in some other way than a way where we can backprop.

01:20.237 --> 01:30.568
So we can't really use this stage one detector right here because this is the one we're training and so we have to backprop through it.

01:30.548 --> 01:38.084
Now an easy proposal is to simply use it anyway, but do like a stop gradient on it, so we don't back prop through it.

01:38.585 --> 01:42.854
That is one way, but the paper decides on a different way.

01:42.995 --> 01:51.072
The paper decides that all of the past basically, right here, right here, and so on,

01:51.052 --> 01:54.495
we'll take a pre-trained object detector.

01:54.795 --> 02:13.471
So not the one we're training currently, but we'll take a pre-trained one that was pre-trained either on something like Coco, which is an object detection dataset, or you can pre-train it on Coco and then fine-tune it on a detask you're interested in, in a single frame fashion.

02:14.472 --> 02:21.058
For whatever way, we'll take a pre-trained object detector or region of interest extractor,

02:21.038 --> 02:30.613
And that will give us, for each frame in the past, will give us also the regions of interest along with the features.

02:32.235 --> 02:32.515
Okay?

02:33.477 --> 02:41.068
And these are the features that we then go and put into the memory bank.

