Okay, so we'll take a pre-trained extractor right here.

02:51.186 --> 02:53.409
That will give us features for regions of interest.

02:53.469 --> 02:58.897
We'll put that into the memory bank and then we will use an attention mechanism to incorporate it.

02:59.257 --> 03:06.807
Now the attention mechanism we can train, but we cannot train the extractor for the features.

03:06.787 --> 03:16.379
And this is the difference to the short-term memory where we can actually train the feature extractor in order to help us with building the memory.

03:17.100 --> 03:21.085
Now the memory is simply built without a goal in mind, basically.

03:21.545 --> 03:30.116
And the attention mechanism basically has to learn that it doesn't work with features that are meant for its task.

03:30.176 --> 03:36.203
It works with features that have been originally created for a different task, and they're not going to change.

03:36.183 --> 03:39.528
But as we'll see, this, you know, can be handled.

03:40.549 --> 03:42.191
So that's what they do.

03:42.412 --> 03:48.200
They incorporate short term and long term memory into their stage two prediction.

03:48.300 --> 03:54.949
And then the stage two prediction simply takes in all of those features and classifies the class of the object.

03:56.070 --> 03:59.595
And that's the architecture of context RCNN.

03:59.756 --> 04:03.000
It's RCNN with long and short term context.

04:05.444 --> 04:12.263
So they describe very different ways of how they built the memory and so on, how they built the features.

